= content_for(:page_title) do
  Getting Started

- # The beliefs that shape the guides: emoji, title, blurb. Rendered as a
- # 2x2 card grid below the intro.
- principles = []
- principles << ["📦", "Consistent Environments", "Docker from the very first command, so every machine — laptop or CI — behaves exactly the same."]
- principles << ["📝", "Readable Templates", "HAML with TailwindCSS + DaisyUI: markup that reads like an outline, styling that stays in the class list."]
- principles << ["🧩", "Components Over Copy-Paste", "Reusable, testable ViewComponents instead of sprawling partials — it's why LocoMotion exists."]
- principles << ["🎛️", "Strong Opinions, All Optional", "UUID primary keys, service objects, defaults your classes always override — take what fits, skip the rest."]

- # The fork: two entry points into the setup guides. Docker is the
- # recommended path; Rails Setup is the shortcut for people who prefer
- # their own machine. Emoji, title, guide id, blurb, recommended flag.
- paths = []
- paths << ["🐳", "Start with Docker", "docker", "Build the containerized development environment first — even rails new runs inside it.", true]
- paths << ["🛤️", "Skip to Rails Setup", "rails_setup", "Comfortable managing Ruby, Node, and Postgres yourself? Jump straight to creating the app.", false]

.max-w-prose
  = doc_info(url: "https://rubyonrails.org", icon: "map", icon_css: "text-secondary") do
    :markdown
      _Loco_**Motion** is more than a component library — it's an opinionated
      path for building Rails applications, and these guides walk it end to
      end.

.prose
  :markdown
    # Getting Started

    Welcome! These guides describe the **LocoMotion way** of building Rails
    apps: the tooling and conventions we reach for on every new project. They
    build on each other in order, but each guide also stands alone, so you
    can cherry-pick whatever fits your team.

    A few beliefs shape everything that follows:

%div{ class: "mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2" }
  - principles.each do |emoji, name, description|
    = daisy_card(css: "bg-base-100 border border-base-300") do
      %span{ class: "text-2xl" }= emoji
      %span{ class: "font-bold" }= name
      %p{ class: "text-sm text-base-content/70" }= description

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "choose-your-path", class: "scroll-mt-24" } Choose Your Path
  :markdown
    The next two guides take you from an empty directory to a running Rails
    app. We recommend starting with Docker — even `rails new` runs inside the
    container — but it is entirely optional:

%div{ class: "mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2" }
  - paths.each do |emoji, name, guide_id, description, recommended|
    = daisy_card(css: "relative bg-base-100 border border-base-300 transition hover:-translate-y-1 hover:shadow-lg", href: guide_path(guide_id), turbo_frame: "_top", turbo_action: "advance", action: "click->nav#refresh") do
      - if recommended
        = daisy_badge("Recommended", css: "badge-success badge-soft absolute top-4 right-4")
      %span{ class: "text-2xl" }= emoji
      %span{ class: "font-bold" }= name
      %p{ class: "text-sm text-base-content/70" }= description

.mt-12.prose
  %h2{ id: "after-setup", class: "scroll-mt-24" } After the App Exists
  :markdown
    Once your app is running, the remaining guides layer on the paradigms one
    at a time: [HAML](#{guide_path("haml")}) templates,
    [building your own components](#{guide_path("building_components")}),
    [debugging & testing](#{guide_path("debugging")}),
    [service objects](#{guide_path("services")}),
    [authentication](#{guide_path("authentication")}), and
    [error handling](#{guide_path("error_handling")}). Read them in order,
    or dip in when the topic comes up.

= doc_note(modifier: :tip, title: "Already Have an App?", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    These guides target brand-new projects. To add LocoMotion's components to
    an existing app, head straight to the [Install docs](#{doc_path("install")}).

= daisy_divider

= doc_buttons(css: "mt-8", current_id: params[:id])
